    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "We could, and we'd get to 4GiB and need a major revision number change on\nour C API. At which point I'd fall back to: if your current problem doesn't\nfit in 2GiB, your future problem isn't solved with 4GiB, and you probably\nwant to change some usage of the APIs.\n\nI'd strongly encourage a design rethink here: aim for much smaller messages\n(kilobytes to megabytes) and leverage streaming.\n\ngRPC currently needs to hold the entire serialized message in memory before\ndeserialization, and so with multi gigabyte messages you're holding huge\namounts of memory hostage, especially compared to a stream.\n\nOn Tue, Aug 30, 2016, 7:17 AM Mark D. Roth notifications@github.com wrote:\n\n> It looks like our current API can't do that, because we encode the max\n> message size as an int, so the maximum supported value is 2147483647. Do\n> you actually need to use a max size larger than that? If so, we might need\n> to make some API changes.\n> \n> @ctiller https://github.com/ctiller, what do you think about changing\n> channel args to use long instead of int?\n> \n> â€”\n> You are receiving this because you were mentioned.\n> \n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\n> https://github.com/grpc/grpc/issues/7882#issuecomment-243453558, or mute\n> the thread\n> https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/AJpudahaLISizxwrUuFVaw7Vk7SPcaljks5qlDthgaJpZM4JtxBn\n> .\n"
  },
